#Text=Jane Dee

#Text=Jane Dee ( née Fromond ) ( 1555 – 1604/5 ) was an English gentlewoman and lady in waiting whose married life is documented in the journals of her husband , the philosopher , occultist , and mathematician John Dee .
#Text=Jane Dee was born in 1555 to Bartholomew Fromond ( or Fromonds ) in Cheam in Surrey . [ 1 ]
#Text=Before her marriage to John Dee , she was a lady in waiting in the entourage of the Countess of Lincoln at the court of Queen Elizabeth I . [ 2 ]
#Text=Her court connections to Elizabeth and to other ladies in waiting may have significantly helped her husband secure patronage . [ 3 ] [ 4 ]
#Text=Marriage
#Text=Jane married John Dee in 1578 when she was 23 and he was 51 .
#Text=Dee was a noted natural philosopher who was particularly interested in divination , Hermetic philosophy and alchemy .
#Text=John Dee
#Text=He acted as an astronomical and medical advisor to Queen Elizabeth and travelled in Europe studying and advising other European nobles . [ 5 ]
#Text=After their marriage , Jane moved to Dee 's home at Mortlake , south-west of London .
#Text=Mortlake Green - geograph.org.uk - 1276862

#Text=They had a large household of family and servants which Jane had a large role in managing , as well as frequent visitors who collaborated with John on a variety of experiments which he conducted in their home .
#Text=Jane and their children also travelled with Dee to Poland in 1584 to work for Albertus Laski , a Polish nobleman .
#Text=She had a son while in Kraków , waiting to join her husband in Prague . [ 6 ]
#Text=We know a great deal about Jane Dee because of the detailed diaries and records kept by her husband . [ 7 ]
#Text=Dee recorded interactions between himself and his wife , arguments , and many details of their household .
#Text=Such detail about the daily life of a sixteenth-century woman is extremely rare .
#Text=Involvement in experimentation
#Text=Dee 's diaries record Jane 's involvement in his scientific investigations .

#Text=He recorded her menstrual cycles , their sexual relations and the births of their children , as well as investigating their miscarried child in an effort to better understand reproduction . [ 8 ]
#Text=In 1582 , Dee began to attempt communications with angels with a new associate , Edward Kelly ( alias Talbot ) who acted as a scryer .
#Text=Jane distrusted Kelley from the start , and Dee records several instances of friction between his wife and associate .
#Text=When Kelley married a young wife , Joanna Cooper , and , according to Dee , neglected her , this may have worsened Jane and Kelley 's relationship , since Jane sympathised with Joanna . [ 9 ]
#Text=Nevertheless , in 1585 , Jane sought Kelley 's help as she attempted to communicate with these angels .
#Text=She asked them about her family 's precarious financial situation and asked for help and reassurance .
#Text=Dee 's papers record her petition :

#Text=We desire , God , of his greate and infinite mercies to grant us the helpe of His hevenly mynisters , that we may by them be directed how or by whom to be ayded and released in this neccessitie for meate and drinke for us and for our familie , wherewith we stand at this instant much oppressed . [ 10 ]
#Text=Jane took an even more involved role in Dee 's experimentation in 1587 , when the Dees and Kelleys were both living in Třeboň .
#Text=Kelley claimed to have communication from the angelic visitors Madimi and Ill that Dee and Kelly should exchange wives in the interest of furthering their philosophical partnership .
#Text=Dee initially objected to the arrangement but was convinced by the insistent urging of the angel through Kelly .

#Text=When informed of the angels suggested arrangement , Jane Dee objected strenuously and ' fell a weeping and trembling for a quarter of an hour ' but John convinced her that it was God 's will that the men share everything .
#Text=Jane and John and Edward Kelley and his wife , Joanna , soon signed an agreement and the physical relationships seem to have been consummated soon after . [ 11 ]
#Text=Some historians have speculated that Jane 's son Theodore , born in 1588 , may have been Kelley 's and that his name was chosen to reference his father . [ 12 ]
#Text=A Magician by Edward Kelly
#Text=Dee and Kelley 's conversations with angels ceased after this communication , and their close collaboration ended in 1589 when Dee and his family returned to England . [ 13 ]
#Text=Later life and death
#Text=After their return to England , Dee continued to record details about Jane , including their sexual activity and frequent cryptic notes , written in Greek meaning ' Jane had them ' .
#Text=The meaning of these notes is not certain , but they have been interpreted as meaning that Jane had dreams or visions . [ 14 ]
#Text=Jane gave birth to three daughters in this period : Madini in 1590 , Frances in 1592 , and Margaret in 1595 . [ 15 ]
#Text=Dee secured a post as warden of the collegiate church in Manchester and Jane and their children moved there with him in 1596 .
#Text=Jane died of the bubonic plague in Manchester in 1605 and was buried at Manchester Cathedral .
#Text=Children
#Text=Jane was John 's second or third wife , but the first with whom he had children .
#Text=The couple had eight children together : four sons named Michael , Theodore , Arthur and Rowland and four daughters named Madinia , Frances , Margaret and Katherine .
#Text=Michael ( d.1594 ) and Theodore ( d.1601 ) predeceased their mother and Madinia , Frances and Margaret may have died of the same bubonic plague as their mother in 1604-5 . [ 16 ]
